<HEAD>Ex-GSA Official Convicted Of Receiving Bribes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A retired <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> official faces a maximum 36-year prison term when he's sentenced Feb. 3 for receiving $ 24,185 in bribes to provide inside information to two businessmen who were found guilty of conspiracy. <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Finotti </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 56, a former manager in <ORGANIZATION> GSA </ORGANIZATION>'s transportation audit branch, was convicted by a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury of receiving the money and the use of a luxury automobile during an 18-month period ending in September 1986 <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, 59, and <PERSON> Carmine </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> DePietro </PERSON>, 53, the former president and former executive vice president, respectively, of <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, were convicted of conspiracy to defraud the government. The charge carries a five-year term. The three defendants were allowed to remain free on bond until their sentencing Feb. 3 by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>. The scheme involved an effort to obtain inside information from <ORGANIZATION> GSA </ORGANIZATION> to help the <LOCATION> Fayetteville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, company, which purchased bills-of-lading at a discount from moving companies that hauled furniture of government employees. Under the arrangement known as factoring, the moving companies in effect paid <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> a premium to receive their money faster than if they waited for the government to pay them directly. Southern Investment, in turn, assumed total liability for any claims for damaged freight that the government filed against the trucking companies. The prosecution presented evidence that <PERSON> Finotti </PERSON> provided information about the reliability of freight haulers that enabled White and <PERSON> DePietro </PERSON> to decide whether to factor a company's bills-of-lading Such information would enable <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> to avoid purchasing moving bills from companies that would likely incur large damage claims, the prosecution contended. The indictment charged that <PERSON> Finotti </PERSON> manipulated the payment of bills-of-lading to benefit Southern Investment. Finotti, of <LOCATION> Waldorf </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, was convicted of conspiracy, bribery, conflict-of-interest, and filing a false government financial disclosure statement that did not report his financial arrangement with <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>.
