<HEAD>More Than 200 Soviet Jews, Armenians Denied Admission As Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities have refused to grant refugee status to more than 200 Soviet Jews and Armenians, but a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official says they could be eligible to enter this country through a system known as parole. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said Friday that the would-be refugees were unable to demonstrate `` a well-founded fear of persecution.'' But one way or another, he said, `` we continue to admit all Soviet Jewish applicants who choose to come to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' The issue was raised by the Union of Councils for Soviet Jews. The private group released two petitions from Soviet Jews in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> awaiting entrance visas to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Most Jews who are permitted to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> have exit permits to emigrate to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. But an overwhelming majority choose to go to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> after they reach <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said of more than 4,000 applications in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> in October and November, less than 200 were found not to qualify for refugees status. But, he said, `` if this occurs, the applicants are, without exception, given the opportunity to apply for parole.'' To be granted parole, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said, applicants must show they would be supported by a relative or a sponsor in the event jobs were not found. The idea is to avoid additional <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> welfare costs. Entering as a refugee provides certain benefits that are not available under parole. These include transportation expenses, some support for resettlement and access to Medicaid. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, he said, 99 applicants, most of whom were Armenians, did not qualify for refugee status during the two months. But, <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said, they also may seek admission under the parole system. <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said there was no change in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continues to call for freedom of emigration for all and continues to admit all Soviet Jewish applicants who choose to come to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` Most qualify as refugees, and in addition some enter as parolees.''
