<HEAD>Ohio Announces Fernald Cleanup Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A historic agreement giving <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> the authority to regulate the federal cleanup of a uranium plant was panned by some neighbors, who plan to pursue their lawsuit against the nuclear weapons factory. Some <PERSON> Fernald </PERSON> residents complained that the agreement between the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> approved by a federal judge Friday fails to commit the agency to spending the $ 1 billion it estimates is needed for the cleanup. `` I do n't really see a commitment that cleanup will be done and I do n't see a timetable as to when it will be done,'' said <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> Fernald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Residents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. Residents also pointed out that the pact provides no money for victims of alleged radioactive contamination from the plant, and that the state has agreed to give up any right to sue the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> or factory contractors. But officials said the consent decree approved here by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spiegel </ORGANIZATION> is a historic document allowing <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> to enforce state environmental regulatory power over the cleanup of the plant, which processes uranium for nuclear weapons assembled elsewhere. The agreement also requires the department to pay the state about $ 1 million in penalties and to reimburse <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> for overseeing the cleanup. The Energy Department has admitted that the plant emitted radioactive uranium dust into the atmosphere over three decades. The plant, known as the Feed Materials Production Center, sits on 1,050 acres 18 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> above the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> aquifer, a water source for 2 million people. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, operations, which include <PERSON> Fernald </PERSON>, said the agreement is evidence of intent to clean up the plant. He said it is not intended as an admission of wrongdoing. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, who announced the agreement with <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Celebrezze </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, said he hoped the decree will prompt <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to give high priority to cleanups of 17 Energy Department plants nationwide, including <PERSON> Fernald </PERSON>. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> estimates it will cost $ 175 billion to clean up the 17 sites over the next 35 years. Only $ 300 million is budgeted for the job next year, he said. <PERSON> Celebrezze </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shank </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> will pursue two federal lawsuits against the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The agreement grew out of two years of negotiations in those cases. <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesley </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> lawyer for the plant's neighbors, said the settlement gives the state no authority over radioactive wastes stored at the plant. <PERSON> Chesley </PERSON> said the neighbors will proceed with their $ 300 million class-action suit at a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> hearing Dec. 16 in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>. `` We have every intention of going forward,'' he said. Plant neighbor <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Clawson </PERSON>, who's represented in the class-action lawsuit, said the agreement falls short of what the Energy Department should do. `` It mainly addressed the hazardous-waste problem, not the radioactive waste problem,'' said <PERSON> Clawson </PERSON>, who lives four miles from the plant. `` They've hardly admitted to anything yet.'' <PERSON> Celebrezze </PERSON> and <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> said the decree is historic because it gives a state a court-enforceable order with which to pressure the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to clean up a nuclear facility `` The decree also extends <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s jurisdiction over <ORGANIZATION> Fernald </ORGANIZATION> to all state and federal hazardous-waste law and regulations,'' <PERSON> Celebrezze </PERSON> said. Both men said it is the first such agreement they know of in the nation. The 37-year-old plant has supplied uranium to the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Rocky Flats plant in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> reactors in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> plant in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION> nuclear complex. The <LOCATION> Sav