<HEAD>Four Stuck In Elevator Overnight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA CROSSE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four people freed from a stalled elevator after spending the night said they kept their spirits up by playing cards and imagining worse predicaments. The four were freed Friday morning after more than 14 hours in the 4-foot-square elevator in this <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> city. `` We were trying to decide what would be worse than this,'' <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Nordgren </PERSON>, 34, said. `` So I asked everyone, Would you rather go into major surgery or go through this again? We all decided surgery.'' <PERSON> Nordgren </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehmann </PERSON>, 39; <PERSON> Adeline </PERSON> `` Kitty'' <PERSON> Reinhart </PERSON>, 59; and her husband, <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON>, 59, said they shared vitamin C tablets and a common toilet made from a plastic shopping bag neatly tied and tucked in a corner. <PERSON> Nordgren </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lehmann </PERSON> are beauticians at a third-floor beauty shop in the building. `` Normally, we never take the elevator when we leave,'' <PERSON> Nordgren </PERSON> said. But she and <PERSON> Lehmann </PERSON> decided to enter the elevator because the <ORGANIZATION> Reinharts </ORGANIZATION> were already in it and were holding the door for them, she said. The elevator became stuck shortly before 6 p.m. Thursday. `` I did n't think that I was going to get out of there alive,'' <PERSON> Lehmann </PERSON> said. She said she eventually overcame her panic and tore a metal plate from a telephone box inside the elevator. She then used it to pry open the elevator door, so fresh air could enter the elevator. The four were not discovered until shortly after 7 a.m., when the owner of a business in the building arrived.
