<HEAD>Quadriplegic Woman Who Plays Keyboard With Mouth Challenging
Anti-begging Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A quadriplegic woman who says she makes $ 2,000 a week playing an electric organ with her mouth is challenging the city's anti-begging ordinance so she can continue her Boardwalk performances in front of casinos. <PERSON> Celestine </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> hearing was postponed Friday, but her lawyers said they were confident they can reach an out-of-court agreement with the city. The 33-year-old woman solicits money from tourists by playing a portable electric keyboard with her tongue and lips. Birth defects left her arms and legs undeveloped, and family members move her on a gurney. Ms. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> said she averages $ 2,000 a week, enough to send her two daughters to private school. In the past several years, she has accumulated dozens of summonses from police enforcing this gambling resort's anti-begging ordinance. On Friday, she was in court to face 23 more. Ms. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>'s attorneys presented a motion challenging the ordinance's constitutionality on grounds that it violates her right of self-expression. `` There is a constitutional right to express oneself artistically and musically,'' argued attorney <PERSON> Justin </PERSON> <PERSON> Loughry </PERSON>. City Prosecutor <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Smoger </PERSON> said he had inadequate time to review the last-minute motion, and said it should be dismissed. Judge <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weekes </PERSON> agreed to delay the hearing to give <PERSON> Smoger </PERSON> time to go over the motion and to give Ms. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>'s attorneys time to continue negotiating with the city. `` I feel like my head is still on the chopping block, because what they decide will determine my future and my life,'' Ms. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> said afterward. `` I believe that the Lord knows somebody's rights were violated, so he sent me here to prove it.'' Ms. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> said that even though the matter is unresolved, she will return to the Boardwalk today to perform. <PERSON> Smoger </PERSON> had been prepared to argue that Ms. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> violated an agreement made with the city two years ago. After a <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> trial in 1986, a subsequent lawsuit and a lot of publicity, the city agreed to allow Ms. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> to perform on the <LOCATION> Boardwalk </LOCATION>. The conditions were that she must stay near <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> and obtain a permit. <PERSON> Smoger </PERSON> said Friday that Ms. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> had done neither. `` Apparently she became disgruntled because <PERSON> Caesar </PERSON>'s -LRB- hotel-casino -RRB- was hiring outdoor bands and it cut into her gratuities, so she moved in front of fire doors at <ORGANIZATION> Bally </ORGANIZATION>'s -LRB- Park Place Casino Hotel -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Smoger </PERSON> said Ms. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> acknowledged that she failed to buy insurance for a permit. Her attorney, <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Freedman </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, said the city offered her standard one-day <LOCATION> Boardwalk </LOCATION> permits normally used for parades, which require a $ 1 million insurance bond. `` That's an unreasonable demand on someone who just plays the keyboard with her tongue,'' Ms. <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> said. `` The rolling chairs on the Boardwalk are only required to carry a $ 300,000 policy, and they're carrying passengers.'' <PERSON> Smoger </PERSON> agreed with Ms. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>'s lawyers that the 1986 agreement was vaguely worded. `` But even if this is resolved, we still have to settle the charges,'' he said.
