<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Newsroom employees at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sun-Times </ORGANIZATION> have a tentative contract for the second time in 10 days, and union and management officials for the city's second-largest newspaper believe the new pact will win approval. `` Short of a strike, this is the best package we can bring to the membership,'' <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON>, chief negotiator for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION>, said after the agreement was announced Friday. `` I feel confident they'll accept it'' in a ratification vote Monday, <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON> said. The newspaper's chief negotiatior, <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Fantl </PERSON>, also praised the agreement. `` Both sides have worked hard and hopefully the -LRB- union's -RRB- members will accept it,'' he said. `` We were able to clear up some misunderstandings and reach an agreement.'' <ORGANIZATION> Sun-Times </ORGANIZATION> workers refused to consider a tentative settlement reached Nov. 22 after a dispute developed over pension conditions. Talks resumed Thursday, with a strike deadline set for noon Friday. Shortly after the deadline, the new agreement was announced. Reporters and others in the newsroom, many of whom had their coats in hand waiting to start a picket line, returned to their desks as word of the settlement spread, said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehmann </PERSON>, a union spokesman and religion reporter. About 250 reporters, editorial and other newsroom workers belong to the guild and have been working without a contract since June 1. Friday's settlement calls for a $ 500 cash bonus Jan. 1 rather than July 1, and 3 percent wage increases in the second and third years of the contract. The night city editor's position will be exempt from the union. Pension benefits were increased by about 6 percent, <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON> said. The pay scale at the newspaper currently ranges from $ 625 a week for starting reporters to $ 895 for reporters with five years' experience The <ORGANIZATION> Sun-Times </ORGANIZATION> has an estimated circulation of 605,000 daily and 614,000 on Sundays. The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>'s circulation is estimated at 765,000 daily and 1.11 million on Sundays.
