<SECOND>PM-India-Bhopal,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Arrested After Bhopal Protesters Throw Stones At Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BHARAT DESAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of shantytown dwellers hurled rocks at police who prevented them from storming the Union Carbide pesticide plant today, the fourth anniversary of a gas leak that killed more than 3,300 people. Police said they arrested at least 200 of the demonstrators. Protest organizers put the arrest total at 500. Most of the protesters, estimated by reporters to number 1,000, came from shantytowns lying in the path of the deadly white cloud of methyl isocyanate that leaked out of the plant Dec. 3, 1984. A few demonstrators suffered minor injuries in scuffles with police, who carried steel-tipped bamboo canes but no firearms. There was no sign of injuries to police. Five activists from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> broke away from police and scaled the 8-foot-high wall surrounding the derelict factory complex, but four of them were grabbed by plainclothes police. The fifth succeeded in climbing a watchtower and briefly hoisted the party flag before police hauled him and the red banner away. `` We want justice! We want justice!'' the crowd shouted in Hindi. Some called for the public hanging of <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, who was president of the U.S.-based multinational corporation when the gas leak occurred. Last year, the Indian government filed murder charges against <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> and other <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and abroad in conjunction with its $ 3 billion damage suit against the <LOCATION> Danbury </LOCATION>, Conn.-based company. The damage suit, initiated in 1986, has bogged down in a maze of legal maneuvers in courts in <LOCATION> Madhya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pradesh </LOCATION> state, which includes <LOCATION> Bhopal </LOCATION>, and in the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> and the others have not responded to summonses on the murder charges. Effigies of <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> were set ablaze outside the <LOCATION> Bhopal </LOCATION> plant Friday night and again today. The Communist Party was the most visible organizer of today's protests, but other opposition parties and activist groups campaigning for the rights of gas victims participated in vigils at the plant gates <PERSON> Balkrishna </PERSON> <PERSON> Gupta </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> secretary for <ORGANIZATION> Madhya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pradesh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION>, said 500 demonstrators were arrested. Police Superintendent <PERSON> Panna </PERSON> <PERSON> Lal </PERSON> said, `` A couple hundred have been arrested, but we have not yet made a head count.'' Reporters who watched the arrested being taken away in eight government buses estimated the total at 400. Police sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said the demonstrators would be released without charge within a few hours. Such detentions are legal under Indian law and are commonly used to break up protests. About 500 uniformed police were on hand for the demonstration. Some had tear gas but did not use it. The government says the official death toll from the 1984 gas leak has reached 3,329. Gas Relief Commissioner <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Saytam </PERSON>, a state official whose office records the deaths and administers relief, said gas victims continue to die at a rate of at least one a day. About 20,000 survivors still suffer from exposure to the gas. Most say they have respiratory and eye problems. Union Carbide said the leak was caused by sabotage by a disgruntled employee.
