<HEAD>Search Continues, Death Count At 1,300</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 8 grafs updating death toll. Pickup 9th, `President
Hussain...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Searchers traveled the river deltas and channels of southern <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> today looking for more than 3,000 people missing after a cyclone that killed at least 1,300 people. Officials said the death toll from Tuesday night's cyclone had reached 900 in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> and 400 in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s neighboring <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bengal </LOCATION> state. <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> newspapers said the <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> toll may be as high as 1,500. The core of the cyclone and the hardest winds struck the lightly populated Sunderbans forest, an expanse of mangrove trees that sprawls across the <LOCATION> Bangladesh-India </LOCATION> border. Officials who spoke on condition of anonymity said most of the forest dwellers were safe. But fishermen who had established colonies along the Sunderbans coast were hit hard. The independent <ORGANIZATION> Ittefaq </ORGANIZATION> newspaper said hundreds of bodies were seen floating in the Sunderbans channels and in the river deltas of <LOCATION> Khulna </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bagerhat </LOCATION> districts east of the forest region. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quereshi </PERSON>, secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> Bangladesh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crescent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, said the death toll had reached 900 and may exceed 1,000. Another official at the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crescent </ORGANIZATION>, the Moslem equivalent of the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, said 3,000 people, mostly fishermen, were missing. The official spoke on condition of anonymity. Bangladeshi newspapers reported death tolls ranging from 1,000 to 1,500. In <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bengal </LOCATION> Finance Minister <PERSON> Asim </PERSON> <PERSON> Dasgupta </PERSON> said 400 deaths had been officially confirmed, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. President <PERSON> Hussain </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> called a special Cabinet meeting Sunday to discuss relief and rehabilitation efforts. <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> officials and foreign relief workers estimated that 40 percent to 70 percent of the rice crop, the staple in the national diet, was destroyed or damaged by the storm. The Sunderbans forest is the home of the royal <LOCATION> Bengal </LOCATION> tiger, but there were no official reports of tiger deaths. The Ittefaq newspaper, however, said hundreds of animals were killed in the Sunderbans. Tiger deaths in the forest have gone unreported in the past. Newspapers have said game wardens like to sell the tiger pelts, and if they reported tiger deaths they might have to give the pelts to the government.
