<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A proposal for direct talks between Tibetan and Chinese leaders on the future of <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> is running into serious difficulties, sources close to <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>'s government-in-exile said today. The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Chinese appear reluctant to meet in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> in January, as proposed by the Tibetans, and would prefer to meet in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, a venue long rejected by the Tibetan side. The sources suggested a <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> venue would portray the Tibetan issue as an internal Chinese matter, rather than an international one that could be perceived as Chinese recognition of Tibetan demands for self-rule. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> in 1949 and annexed it a year later. Many Tibetans have long insisted on independence for their Himalayan mountain region, but their spiritual and temporal leader, the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>, suggested in June that <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> could become `` a self-governing democratic politicial entity ... in association with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.'' In his biggest concession so far, the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> also said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> could continue to handle <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>'s foreign relations and keep troops on Tibetan soil. Senior Tibetan officials in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> declined to confirm the reports that the Chinese were reluctant to meet in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Lodi </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyari </PERSON>, minister for information and international relations in the self-styled government-in-exile, said: `` We are not denying them.'' The Chinese Embassy in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> had no reply to the report. The embassy's chief spokeswoman was out of town, and an aide said no one else could comment. The reports of Chinese reluctanc