<HEAD>Feds Change Loan-as-Income Policy After Nevada Lawsuit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf to ADD HHS comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal government has reversed its policy of counting loans as income for welfare recipients after a <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> lawsuit showed the practice violated the law since its inception five years ago, officials said. The lawsuit and similar cases in other states, including <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, prompted the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> to chang the policy Tuesday, according to a motion filed Friday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. `` We feel good. We feel real good,'' said attorney <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nevada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, which represents poor people. <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardett </PERSON> said he could not say how many people nationally would be affected by the policy change. The motion filed by Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> asked Judge <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> to delay a final decision in the 1986 class-action lawsuit filed by <ORGANIZATION> Nevada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> on behalf of state residents denied benefits under the loan policy. The <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> was named as a third party in the lawsuit but was not involved in a proposed settlement between the state and <ORGANIZATION> Nevada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. Anticipating the judge's ruling against the federal government in the case, attorneys for the federal agency requested a 30-day delay in a final order so they also could work out a settlement. The proposed settlement, which must be approved by <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, was filed Wednesday. In the proposed settlement, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> agreed to repay 60 people $ 11,767 for welfare payments that were denied when personal loans were counted as income, making them ineligible for benefits. Deputy state Welfare Division Administrator <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Willden </PERSON> said he was pleased by the federal government's latest move. The Welfare Division had disagreed with the loan-as-income policy since federal authorities forced it on the states in 1983, he said. The Aid to Dependent Children program is funded 50 percent by the federal government. `` The loans should have never been counted,'' <PERSON> Willden </PERSON> said. `` But we had no choice. We would have lost our federal funding. I think this lawsuit did turn the policy around. `` It was clearly shown that the administration's regulations were violating the welfare laws.'' <PERSON> Willden </PERSON> said it cost <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> more than $ 40,000 to locate people unqualified for welfare benefits by the loan policy. Initial estimates showed as many as 3,000 people in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> might have been affected by the policy, but most could not be found. Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION> issued a preliminary injunction preventing the Welfare Division from counting loans as income in determining benefit eligibility pending the outcome of the lawsuit.
