<HEAD>Snail Fever Strikes 1 Million In Southern China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The blood disease snail fever has been contracted by 1 million people in southern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and has made a comeback in some areas where it had previously been wiped out, an official daily said today. The People's Daily said the resurgence of the occasionally fatal disease occurred because of lax control by local governments and a drop in funding to eradicate the disease-bearing oncomelania, a freshwater snail. The overseas edition of the daily said the disease has returned to <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> and areas of the southern provinces of <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Fujian </LOCATION> where it had previously been eliminated. Snail fever, also known as schistosomiasis, is prevalent in 12 provinces, and is most serious in riverside or swampy areas of <LOCATION> Hubei </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jiangxi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Anhui </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jiangsu </LOCATION> provinces. The disease, transmitted into the bloodstream by a parasite, results in fever, distended stomach, rashes, inflammation of the liver and in severe cases death. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> says it has cured more than 11 million sufferers, or 95 percent of all victims of the disease, since 1949.
