<SECOND>PM-Contra Arms,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge to Decide if U.S. Was At War With Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge agreed to decide if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was at war with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> in the mid-1980s, the key issue in the case against six men accused of illegally providing military aid to the Contras. In a pretrial hearing Friday, the defendants argued that the Neutrality Act, under which they were indicted, applies only to nations with which the nation is at peace, and said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> conducted a de facto war against <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Sandinista government. They are asking that the case against them be dismissed. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roettger </PERSON> held the hearing on the `` at-peace'' issue over the objections of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office, which sought to delay the matter until the trial `` It will indeed be an historical decision, whatever the court determines,'' said defense attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Savitz </PERSON>. <PERSON> Roettger </PERSON> continued the hearing until Jan. 5, and said he would decide the issue shortly thereafter. The defense Friday presented volumes of Iran-Contra committee and <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> reports to back up its contention that even during the periods when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> halted military aid to the rebels, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration continued to run a war against the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>. Contra leader <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>, whose brother <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON> is one of the defendants, took the stand to testify that former <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> provided the rebels with $ 32 million during the congressional cutoff, much of which was spent on arms. He said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support actually increased during the 1984-85 period of the aid cutoff and the defendants' alleged illegal activities. `` They told us that the president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would continue to solicit funds for us,'' sai <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>. `` They said they would continue to support us, and that we should not give up.'' Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Debelier </PERSON> tried to draw distinctions between <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military actions, including the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> War, saying that in those cases the executive branch received congressional support. The judge seemed to dismiss that argument, however, mentioning <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and raids on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. `` The only distinction with the Nicaraguan situation is that you have one branch of government expressing its displeasure,'' <PERSON> Roettger </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Debelier </PERSON> noted that much of the testimony regarding support for the Contras revolved around commitments made and privately raised funds provided by <PERSON> North </PERSON>, who is under indictment for his role in aiding the rebels. `` You ca n't say that because two or three members of the executive branch are going to solicit funds for the Contras, that is the same as binding the government'' to warlike activities in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, the prosecutor said. The group was indicted in June after charges of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration foot-dragging during the highly publicized investigation. Opponents of aid to the Contras accused Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> of stalling the case because it threatened to uncover illegal activities by <PERSON> North </PERSON>. When the indictment _ along with a similar one filed against six other men accused of running a Contra training camp in the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> _ was finally made public, it accused Contra supporters of violating the Neutrality Act by launching operations against the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> government from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soil from October 1984 to March 1985. The seven original defentants were <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Posey </PERSON>, head of the Alabama-based Civilian Material Assistance group; <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>, a former supply manager for the rebels; <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>'s former bodyguard; <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON>, a former mercenary who turned against the effort and went to authorities; <PERSON> Maco </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, a wealthy former <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> businessman and state official who now lives in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Coutin </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> and former <ORGANIZATION> CMA </ORGANIZATION> liaison in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, a conservative Cuban-American stockbroker The indictment accuses them of recruiting and training mercenaries to fight with Contras, supplying them with equipment, leading them on expeditions, including one aimed at blowing up a Nicaraguan bridge, and violating firearms laws. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> allegedly financed some of the activities. Some of the defendants, including <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Posey </PERSON>, have produced documents showing the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and other agencies were aware of their activities, and have said that knowledge of their activities went all the way to the White House. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> pleaded guilty. He was fined $ 50 and sentenced to a day of probation. The other six defendants continue to fight the charges.
