<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Reforms,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reforms Make Effort to Compromise with Republics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> today published details of its new government structure that retains central control over the 15 republics while attempting to compromise with their demands for more autonomy. Publication in all major Soviet daily newspapers gave Soviet citizens their first look at the final version of a political structure that will govern them beginning in March. After an intense five-week public debate in which a quarter million suggestions were made for changes, the Supreme Soviet, or parliament, and its Presidium, the country's highest executive body, approved changes in about half the articles. The final project, which President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has said is crucial to his reform effort, was approved Thursday by the 1,500-member Supreme Soviet with five `` no'' votes. The reforms will establish a <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, two-thirds by popular vote and a third by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, trade unions and other organizations. The deputies will pick members of a smaller two-house Supreme Soviet that will meet twice a year for four months at a time. The current body meets several days a year. The president becomes the head of the the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and has the right to conduct international negotiations and sign treaties. Among the articles apparently watered down in the final draft was one that republics opposed because they said it called into question their right to secede from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The final draft gave the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies the power to `` make decisions on matters of national-state structure which are in the jurisdiction of the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics.'' Previous language had given it the power to make decisions `` on the composition of the U.S.S.R.'' The new law establishes similar Congresses of People's Deputies in the 15 republics as well, but leaves it to the republics' constitutions to outline their powers The original draft included a lengthy list of powers of the republics' congresses. That also appeared to be an effort to compromise with officials from the republics, especially <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>. Estonian President <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruutel </PERSON>, in a speech to the Supreme Soviet, said the republic did not want to be forced to form a <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is impossible to find an optimum -LRB- political system -RRB- for all regions of the country,'' <PERSON> Ruutel </PERSON> said. `` So we have created our own.'' <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> has led opposition to the constitutional changes. On Nov. 16 its Supreme Soviet made a `` declaration of sovereignty'' in internal affairs, and proclaimed its right to approve all new national laws. The national government declared the move unconstitutional. The final version of the law gives the republics more representatives in the Soviet of <ORGANIZATION> Nationalities </ORGANIZATION>, one of the two houses of the Supreme Soviet, and also ensures they be represented on a new constitutional oversight commission. It orders directives of the central government to be published in the languages of the republics. But it also gives the national Presidium specific powers to ensure that the constitutions and laws of the republics correspond to the national constitution. There were complaints that giving organizations such as the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and unions the right to elect one-third of the members of the national <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would violate the principle of one man, one vote, by allowing union or party members to vote more than once, or even hold several seats. The final draft says that in selecting the Supreme Soviet, the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> must make sure that members of the party or other organizations not be over-represented. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, in a speech Nov. 29, told the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> it would have the right under the law to veto any order from him or from the Presidium. Under the new law, however, the presidency still is more powerful than the largely ceremonial post <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> now holds. The new structure goes into effect with the election of the new <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies on March 26, 1989.
</TEXT>
