<HEAD>Inauguration Has Something For Everyone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's bicentennial inaugural festivities next month have something for everyone, from glamour-seekers and history buffs to children, chocolate lovers and ordinary citizens trying to get in on the action. `` We want to make sure that everybody who wishes to can participate,'' said <PERSON> Ownie </PERSON> <PERSON> McBride </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the American Bicentennial Presidential Inaugural Committee. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will be sworn in Jan. 20 as president in the nation's 51st formal inaugural ceremony, amid <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flags from 1789, 1889 and 1989 and red bunting recalling <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>'s inauguration 200 years ago The oath-taking on the West Front of the Capitol, overlooking the city and the Mall, will be a solemn contrast to four days full of official and unofficial parties, pageants, balls, receptions, galas, salutes, celebrations and festivals. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Studdert </PERSON>, director of the presidential inaugural committee, has said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> inauguration will feature more free activities than ever before. A sketchy schedule released last week shows at least three major events for children and youth, including a festival entitled `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> to <PERSON> George </PERSON> _ Two Hundred Years.'' Some of the capital's best known landmarks will once again be the sites of inaugural balls, including the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> and Space Museum, the <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and the grandly restored Union Station. The inaugural planners' goal of broad participation is in keeping with the open, relaxed style of <PERSON> George </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. But there will be glamour aplenty, what with nine balls and innumerable other upscale events. Roll Call, the weekly <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> newspaper, published a special inauguration preview section suggesting `` 10 places to throw your inaugural party'' and noting that `` for inaugural week, a limo can be a must.'' The newspaper also canvassed fashion experts at local department stores and concluded that inaugural dress this year will run to `` ultra-formal, sophisticated classics.'' Capital area hotels are pulling out all the stops for inauguration week guests, with special menus, patriotic decorations and individual perks including chocolate elephant lollipops, white chocolate replicas of the White House and six-inch square chocolate pianos filled with sweets. `` It's a grand piano. The lid is up. The truffles and goodies are inside the piano where the strings would be,'' explained Park Hyatt spokeswoman <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>. `` You can eat the whole blooming piano.'' Officials at the <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inaugural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> declined to discuss how much money they hope to raise to pay for the festivities. The price tag could be higher than ever before, since a new law requires the committee to reimburse the Pentagon for its expenses in helping plan, staff and execute inaugural activities. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s 1985 inauguration committee raised more than $ 12 million to pay for its events, but a congressional study found that the use of federal employees cost taxpayers another $ 15.5 million. The Pentagon alone spent $ 10 million and used 8,400 military personnel who served as chauffeurs and escorts, musicians and coat-checkers, photographers and even organizers of receiving lines. The two exceptions to the reimbursement rule are the inaugural ceremony and a lunch for the president, vice president and congressional leaders, both traditionally organized by the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Inaugural Ceremonies. The committee will distribute 70,000 inaugural tickets to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, 40,000 to Republicans and another 30,000 to the press, governors, diplomats and other customary guests. `` If if's too cold to have it outside, the guest list goes from 140,000 to approximately 950,'' the amount that will fit inside the <ORGANIZATION> Capitol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rotunda </ORGANIZATION>, said congressional committee director <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruehling </PERSON>. He said preparations for an indoor ceremony will be made in advance, `` which guarantees that it wo n't happen.'' While <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> took his first oath outside the Capitol in balmy 55-degree weather, a record high for Inauguration Day, his second inaugural ceremony was forced indoors due to a record low temperature of 7 degrees. The parade was canceled, to the disappointment of hundreds of thousands of prospective spectators and young marching band members. There was one inaugural week parade in 1985 _ a <ORGANIZATION> Rainbow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> march down <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> led by <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, a two-time contender for the Democratic presidential nomination. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> capped the march by blasting <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for `` taking from the poor and giving to the rich'' and characterized the inaugural goings-on as `` vulgar expressions of ostentatiousness, private airplanes and long limousines and $ 25,000 dresses and diamonds from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' This year the mood is somewhat different. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> lunched with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at the White House last week and came away smiling. `` I'm impressed with the vice president's openness,'' he said `` Whatever I can do in some role, I would.''
