<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Looking for something fashionable yet practical for the woman who lives a life of danger? Give her bullet-resistant furs, in a wide variety of styles. The furs are lined with <PERSON> Kevlar </PERSON>, a synthetic fiber that is five times stronger than its weight in steel and is used in bullet-proof vests worn by police. `` I see the full fur coats being worn by movie stars, actresses, <PERSON> Ivana </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump-types </PERSON>, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, maybe even <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Andrilli </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Guardian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, and a distributor of Kevlar. As he spoke, a <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> look-alike swept into the showroom of <ORGANIZATION> Jiuliana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Originals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in a full-length $ 80,000 Russian sable coat. Another model followed in a three-quarter-length $ 8,500 fox jacket of light brown and white-flecked fur. `` A Madonna-rock-star-type would wear a coat like this,'' said furrier <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zizzo </PERSON>. He and his mother, <PERSON> Jiuliana </PERSON> <PERSON> Zizzo </PERSON>, designed the coats. A woman in jeans modeled a butter-soft black leather bomber jacket lined with reversible black mink and Kevlar, which retails for $ 5,500. `` We do n't want someone to buy a coat they would n't want to wear,'' <PERSON> Zizzo </PERSON> said. `` They can wear these coats every day, so they can utilize the protection.'' `` We can do anything,'' <PERSON> Zizzo </PERSON> said. `` If <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> wanted shoes, we could do bullet-resistant shoes for her.''
