<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State employees on the top half of the 20-story <ORGANIZATION> Sillers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Building </ORGANIZATION> freeze in the morning. In the afternoon, they swelter. And opening the windows? Well, that's another story. `` When it gets cold, it's hard to sit at your desk. We keep the coffee pots going eight hours a day up here. The secretaries have these heavy coats on at their typewriters,'' said <PERSON> Liz </PERSON> <PERSON> Cleveland </PERSON>, whose office is on the 13th floor. It's been about two months since the demise of the fans that run the heating and cooling system at the top of one of downtown <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s tallest buildings. While it's cold in the mornings, sunlight streaming through the windows causes the temperature to soar during the day. `` What we've been doing is prying open the windows in the afternoon, but on the 13th floor, it's like sitting in the cockpit of a helicopter,'' said <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, manager of the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>'s export-import office. `` One day my door blew shut and all the ceiling tiles blew out of my office.'' New fans had to be specially ordered, so the top floors probably wo n't be comfortable until after the Christmas holidays, said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capitol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Facilities </ORGANIZATION>.
