<HEAD>Panic Buying of Salt Hits Canton</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Panic buying of salt hit <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s southern city of <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION>, sending its prices soaring in some privately run food stores, a pro-Beijing newspaper reported Saturday. The Chinese-language New Evening Post said the price rises violated regulations and the merchants would be held responsible. The report did not elaborate. Rumors that vouchers would be needed to buy salt resulted in long customer lines outside several food stores in <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> recently, the newspaper said. <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> is about 90 miles west of this British colony. The price of salt rose from 10 cents to 35 cents at the stores, the newspaper reported without giving the unit of measure of the salt. Provincial and city governments said warehouses were stocked and no voucher program existed, the newspaper reported. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economic reform policy has been slowed by inflation that has soared to a post-1950s high of more than 26 percent. There have been recent reports of panic buying of textiles in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> and salt in 19 areas, where authorities immediately imposed rations.
