<HEAD>Soviets and Afghan Rebels Meet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABDULLAH AL-SHEHRI</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet officials and Afghan guerrillas today began informal talks on prisoners of war, the future relationship between <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and the future of the Soviet-backed <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government. The face-to-face talks in <LOCATION> Taif </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> resort 600 miles from <LOCATION> Riyadh </LOCATION>, were the first between the Soviets and a seven-group guerrilla alliance since the 1979 Soviet invasion of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The Soviets have met other rebel groups on two occasions earlier this year. Formal negotiations were expected to begin later today or Sunday, sources close to the talks said. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> was chosen as a venue by the Afghan resistance groups because of the influence it wields in the Islamic world. The kingdom has said repeatedly it would consider establishing ties with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> only after Soviet troops complete their withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The Soviets intervened there in December 1979. The head of the Soviet delegation was <PERSON> Yuli </PERSON> <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON>, a deputy foreign minister who recently was named ambassador to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, the sources said on condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Burhanuddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabbani </PERSON>, leader of the loose alliance of Afghan resistance groups based in <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, has been in the kingdom for two weeks. Other rebel leaders were expected to join the official talks later. <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON> is the second Soviet official to visit <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> in less than a year. <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Polyakov </PERSON>, another deputy foreign minister, came in February in what was seen then as a move toward rapprochement between the two countrues. <PERSON> Rabbani </PERSON> has stressed that the overriding focus for the rebels during the talks will be on complete withdrawal of Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. More than half of the 100,000 troops have left since <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> signed a U.N.-sponsored accord in April calling for withdrawal. The rest of the troops were supposed to be out by Feb. 15, but the Soviets recently halted the withdrawal to protest what they called continued funding of the guerrillas by <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and the Marxist government of President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> are now seeking to convene an international conference to demilitarize <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and set up a coalition government with the rebels. <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrovsky </PERSON>, also a Soviet deputy foreign minister, told reporters in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on Friday that the <LOCATION> Vorontsov-Rabbani </LOCATION> meeting was arranged by the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> government with the cooperation of the Afghan government. He said no representatives of <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s government or <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, the main backer of the rebels, will attend the meeting.
