ecommended that the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> seek repeal of the program or find an agency more familiar with state grant programs to run it. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> wanted states to use the money to find and help homeless people eligible for benefits, particularly the mentally and physically disabled who are entitled to Supplemental Security Income, <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> said in the Dec. 2 letter. `` It's really the season that warrants it,'' he said in an interview. `` Here we are with winter upon us. There are people out on the streets who are obviously and clearly qualified for SSI benefits. The purpose of the legislation was to help states reach out and identify those individuals. ... We felt we ought to bring it to the attention of the president-elect.'' <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gambino </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> not only failed to allocate money for the outreach grant program but in fact gave the agency less money in its overall budget than it requested for fiscal 1988 and 1989. `` Therefore we have to rely on other alternative means'' to reach the homeless, <PERSON> Gambino </PERSON> said. He said employees at the 1,300 <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> offices nationwide work closely with shelters and advocacy groups to make sure the homeless receive benefits. `` Commissioner <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> is very much concerned that we deliver our services compassionately and fairly to the homeless. We think we're doing a good job of it,'' <PERSON> Gambino </PERSON> said <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> called that claim `` baloney. ... They're not doing any kind of outreach that I can see. Obviously it was the congressional view that the kind of work that was needed was not being done.'' He said there was no specific allocation because <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> assumed the agency would fund the relatively tiny grant program from its general budget. At the same time she was fighting the homeless program, <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> said, <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> was supporting a $ 1.6 million plan to send decorative certificates, suitable for framing, to Social Security beneficiaries. <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> approved the plan despite a recommendation to scrap it, according to documents supplied by <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>' office. `` It's a nutty idea,'' <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> said. `` It contrasts what she thinks money ought to be spent for as opposed to what the real needs of people are.'' <PERSON> Gambino </PERSON> said <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> still thinks the certificates are a good idea but they have n't been instituted. `` We have n't killed the proposal, but it is not a high priority at this time based on its cost and our funding situation,'' he said.
