<HEAD>Post-Challenger Era Includes New Generation of Astronauts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Space shuttle Atlantis is carrying two space newcomers, part of a new generation of astronauts with a look and background unlike that of the all-white, crew-cut, All American team who rode the Mercury capsules. Nine more rookies have been named to four future flights, and a new class of astronauts is in training to fill spots vacated by veterans who took other jobs after the shuttle Challenger exploded on Jan. 28, 1986. The space program now has 93 men and women astronauts, with a nearly even mix of experienced space travelers and those who have never flown into space. Within 10 years, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> is expected to add more as it responds to the demand of more shuttle flights and begins construction of the space station. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s new astronauts are far different from the seven original ones. The first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> astronauts were all military test pilots, all male and all white. All <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrongs </PERSON> in flight suits. The space shuttles, with room for up to seven crew members, opened new opportunities. In 1978, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> selected women and men, pilots and non-pilots, and black, white, Hispanic and Asian candidates. The newest group, chosen last year, includes the first black woman astronaut, Dr. <PERSON> Mae </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jemison </PERSON>, a physician, and the first <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guardsman </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Melnick </PERSON>. Another group is scheduled to be chosen in January 1990. Despite the loss of the seven Challenger astronauts, the number of applications has increased since the accident, <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> said. The competition seems to have stiffened over the years, said