<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Reforms     12-03 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Reforms,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reforms Keep Tight Rein on Republics, Restructure Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet citizens got their first look Saturday at the fine points of a new political system that keeps a tight rein on the 15 republics, strengthens the presidency and builds a more dynamic parliament. Major daily Soviet newspapers published details of the reforms, which were approved Thursday by the Supreme Soviet parliament and will go into effect with elections next March 26. The reforms, adopted after five weeks of intense public debate, attempt to forge a compromise between demands by the republics for autonomy and the need for central control by the government in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. But a lawyer for a grass-roots Lithuanian movement scoffed at compromises made to the restive republics and said his organization was writing a complaint over President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms that will arrive at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> about the same time the Soviet leader does `` All the things that choked and are choking us are still there,'' <PERSON> Kazimieras </PERSON> <PERSON> Motieka </PERSON>, a member of the governing council of the Sajudis movement, said in a telephone interview from the Lithuanian capital of <LOCATION> Vilnius </LOCATION>. The new system establishes a 2,250-member <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies that will include for the first time members of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, trade union and other organizations as well as representatives chosen on the basis of geographical districts and ethnic homelands The congress will choose a smaller, more active Supreme Soviet that is to meet eight months instead of several days a year. Several of the 15 republics, especially the Baltic republics of Lithuanian, <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, have complained that the laws as proposed by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in October concentrated too much power in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Motieka </PERSON> said the new laws give the national parliament wide power over the economy in the republics. By including property under the jurisdication of the national Supreme Soviet, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> established `` that what is in our republic is not our property,'' he said. `` We ca n't organize our own agriculture,'' he said. `` We ca n't even change wages. Among the articles changed in the final draft of the reform was one opposed by republics because they said it called into question their right to secede from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The final version gave the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies power to `` make decisions on matters of national-state structure which are in the jurisdiction of the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics.'' Previous language had given it the power to make decisions `` on the composition of the U.S.S.R.'' The language appeared weaker, but <PERSON> Motieka </PERSON> contended that the change was in words only. <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> has led opposition to the constitutional changes. On Nov. 16 its Supreme Soviet made a `` declaration of sovereignty'' in internal affairs and proclaimed its right to approve all new national laws. The national government declared that move unconstitutional, but the Estonian parliament meets Monday to discuss further expressions of autonomy. The final version of the law gives republics more representatives in one of the two houses of the Supreme Soviet and representation on a new constitutional oversight commission. It orders directives of the central government to be published in the languages of the republics. But it also gives the national Presidium specific powers to ensure that the constitutions and laws of the republics correspond to the national constitution. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> leaves Monday for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where he will address the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and meet with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. He then travels to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Motieka </PERSON> said the governing council of <LOCATION> Sajudis </LOCATION> agreed during a session Saturday to send a complaint to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. A draft was being written and a vote would be taken Sunday, he said.
