mmunicate with the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, more committed to openness and internal reform.'' `` This offers promise but in no way should lessen our commitment to peace through strength _ a policy we must continue,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> In another speech a day later, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> again referred to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> and said: `` They are serious people. They know they must change. After 70 years of the Marxist-Leninist state, it's pretty hard to explain to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> people why they do n't have either bread or freedom, why the food situation is worse than it was a decade ago, or why life expectancy has dropped. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> `` is clearly a different kind of Soviet leader than we have seen recently. He is prepared to take radical steps. He is able to reverse course when Soviet policies fail, when the costs become too high.'' A week before he was elected, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that should he become president, he would be prepared to meet with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> `` at the earliest time that would serve the interests of world peace.'' He said he would want to engage in `` a serious and direct examination of where we are and how we can best go forward toward further arms reductions, a decrease in regional tensions and further adherence to human rights and thus toward a surer peace.''
