<HEAD>Walesa Told He May Travel to France</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, who has not been allowed to leave <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> since 1981, has been given permission to travel to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> later this month, his wife said Saturday. The change in policy will allow him to attend a ceremony in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> on Dec. 10 marking the 40th anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, who was invited by French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, applied for a passport last week and was informed on Saturday that he may pick it up Monday, said <PERSON> Danuta </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, speaking from the couple's home in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> was suffering from a flu and cold and was unable to come to the telephone. `` He has gotten a passport. Someone called from the passport office and said he can come and pick it up on Monday,'' she said. `` He's happy that he's going to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and will breathe some different air.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said she would remain in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and take care of the couple's eight children. An aide, <PERSON> Piotr </PERSON> <PERSON> Konopka </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> would work his travel plans out soon and decide whether to take along other members of the banned Solidarity union. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Olechowski </PERSON> was due to return Sunday from an official visit to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. Asked about <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s passport application earlier in the week, he had said he expected it to be issued. The trip would be the first time the 1983 Noble Peace Prize winner received permission to leave <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> since the imposition of martial law at the end of 1981. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> had visited <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in October of that year. Polish citizens must apply for a passport whenever they wish to travel to a non-socialist country. Travel restrictions have been eased in recent years, although some passports are still denied for political reasons. In March, the government denied <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> permission to attend an international trade union conference in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>.
