Reykjavik</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said today he feels nostalgic as he faces his last session with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, and will use the meeting to introduce his successor as a man who represents `` change, yes, but also continuity.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in his weekly rado address delivered from Camp David, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, said he was looking forward to the upcoming meeting and luncheon on Wednesday, set on Governors Island in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The president recalled that since he first met the Soviet leader in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> in 1985, the U.S.-Soviet relationship has developed and resulted in the first agreement to get rid of an entire class of nuclear weapons. `` This will be our last such meeting, and I must admit that I would not have predicted after first taking office, that some day I would be waxing nostalgic about my meetings with Soviet leaders,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, in a reference to his days as an ardent anti-communist. `` But here we are, for the fifth time, Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and I together, in the hope of furthering peace.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> pointed out that despite their agreement on arms control, there is much work to be done over differences on that subject, and on human rights, regional problems, and in bilateral relations. The goal of improved U.S.-Sviet relations `` must continue byond any single presidency or term of office,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, adding that he is `` particularly delighted'' that President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will join the meeting. `` No one is better versed in the details of Soviet-American relations or has a stronger foreign policy portfolio than our vice president,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` So, on our get-together next week ... you can be sure I'll be telling Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> that <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> represents change, yes, but also continuity,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s national security adviser, Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, says <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials expect no surprises at the luncheon meeting next week, and that if <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> presents some totally unexpected proposal, as the Soviet leader did in <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION> two years ago, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials will not allow themselves to be forced to make a snap reply. The <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION> summit collapsed when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> disagreed over the Soviet leader's demand that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> president substantially downgrade his Star Wars missile-defense program. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials were widely criticized after the October 1986 summit, with political opponents accusing the American side of having been unprepared to cope with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s bold proposal. `` Based on what we have heard from the Soviets, I am not aware of any that they're planning to put down on the table,'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said. `` But I do n't have, obviously, complete control over what the general secretary might suggest,'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> continued. `` And if he does have some ideas that we have not heard before, we will listen carefully, respond or take them under advisement as the case may be.'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> also said that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have `` no major new proposals to put down on the table'' on Governors Island in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> next Wednesday.
