<SECOND>AM-Social Security-Disability,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commissioner Kills Staff Draft That Sparked Controversy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Social Security Commissioner <PERSON> Dorcas </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON>, faced with an outcry over possible changes in disability rules, said Saturday she has rejected the draft proposal that sparked the furor. She said the draft had `` generated inaccurate information and caused undue alarm to the American public.'' She said she remains convinced that the agency's hearings and appeals process needs reform, but the staff-suggested proposal did not meet her criteria of making the system `` more equitable, compassionate and efficient.'' `` I believe that <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- can do better and have, therefore, rejected it,'' she said in a four-page statement. The furor erupted last month when The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration was considering restricting the right of Social Security applicants to introduce new evidence upon appeal. Thirty-five senators, including one Republican, <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Durenburger </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, sent a letter to President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Wednesday urging him to repudiate the policy change. <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON>, in her statement, said her agency `` is deeply committed to improving the hearings and appeals process to ensure that claimants receive fair, timely and accurate decisions when appealing an unfavorable government decision.' She said it was important to ensure that the system is compassionate, since most appeals involve disability claims. She said people are also entitled to `` a speedy decision.'' The agency gets 300,000 requests a year for hearings before its 800 administrative law judges, and it takes an average of nearly two years to appeal a claim through the administrative process to the federal courts. <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> said 80 percent of Social Security beneficiaries now are represented at these hearings by lawyers, and the agency each year `` pays almost $ 100 million in fees to attorneys out of the past due benefits of claimants who win benefits on appeal.'' More than half those who appeal disability denials eventually win benefits. The proposal drafted by the agency's <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hearings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> would have required claimants to submit all evidence at least seven days in advance of a hearing before an administrative law judge. Social Security officials said the draft had not even reached <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON>'s desk when it became public. It proved an acute embarrassment for <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON>, often mentioned as a contender for secretary of health and human services in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. She said that `` because confidence in our policy-making process has been questioned, I removed the draft proposal from the routine process and personally reviewed it.'' Disability benefit cutoffs were a major source of controversy in the early years of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, when more than 1 million disability beneficiaries had their cases reviewed and more than 40 percent were ordered off the rolls. More than half won on appeal, and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the administration eased up on the reviews. <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> was not commissioner then. In her statement, <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> said, `` There is nearly unanimous agreement that the current hearings and appeals process needs reform. In addition to our own concerns, a vast amount of criticism has also come from frustrated claimants, attorneys, the courts and the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.'' To improve it, she said, `` we need an open and honest exchange of ideas. We must explore all options and alternatives.'' She said she has asked her Disability Review Council, chaired by Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Affeldt </PERSON>, to review the hearings and appeals process. She also invited leaders of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and `` all interested parties'' to work together with her to make the process `` fairer, more equitable and more responsive to the needs of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> public.''
