<HEAD>President Says He Will Dissolve Parliament, Call Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s president said Saturday he will dissolve <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> Dec. 20, a day after presidential elections, to give his successor `` the benefit of the views of the present electorate.'' President <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> also said he would call general elections six months ahead of schedule, on Feb. 15 instead of the scheduled balloting next August. He said new legislators would begin their six-year terms March 9. Opposition parties and the powerful <PERSON> Buddhist </PERSON> clergy have urged <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> to disband <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> before the presidential elections in an effort to end the ethnic civil war that has wracked this <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> island since 1983. Nearly 10,000 people have died in the fighting. But <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> has resisted their calls, saying he would dissolve <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> after his successor is chosen. `` I feel that an opportunity should be given to the people to elect a new <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> so that the new president should have the benefit of the views of the present electorate,'' the 82-year-old leader said in a speech broadcast on state-run radio and television. <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>, who is ending a political career that spans 45 years, is prohibited by law from seeking a third six-year term. He and his <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> have been in power since 1977, extending their terms through a 1982 referendum rather than a general election. A Sinhalese extremist group, the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, has called for the nation's estimated 9.3 million eligible voters to boycott the presidential race, charging <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>'s government is incapable of conducting a fair election. The front, a shadowy group known more for its violent acts than its Marxist ideology, opposes a peace accord aimed at ending the 5-year-old insurgency by Tamil militants fighting for a separate homeland in the north and east provinces. It also wants an estimated 47,000 Indian peacekeeping troops trying to supervise the accord withdrawn from the island. Sinhalese extremists contend the accord grants too many concessions to the Tamils, who are mostly Hindu and comprise 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people. The predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> Sinhalese comprise 75 percent of the population and control the government and the military. The front has vowed to kill anyone who supports the accord and has been blamed for more than 900 political murders since the pact was signed in July 1987. Most of the victims have been government supporters. Earlier Saturday, <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lankan </LOCATION> soldiers hunting for Sinhalese rebels conducted a house-to-house search in the <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Panadura </LOCATION> after imposing a 22-hour curfew, which expires early Sunday. More than 100 suspects were taken into custody, but most were released, according to a military official, who can not be identified under briefing rules. The operation was called after authorities received information that front members planned to launch a nationwide strike next week in an effort to destablize the government. In his speech Saturday night, <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> said political unrest had hampered implementation of many of his government's programs. However, he told listeners: `` I value especially whatever I have been able to do to preserve the rights of my people to elect their representatives, to point out their mistakes and to replace them through elections, thus preserving the fundamental freedoms of democracy.''
