' had been agreed on by the rebels and <PERSON> Caridi </PERSON>. `` Seineldin has not surrendered nor does he intend to,'' said <PERSON> Jardin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Seineldin </PERSON>, a combat veteran of the 1982 <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> War with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, told reporters Friday he and his men did not want to overturn the government, but sought to `` restore military honor to the army and review the trials that punish the just and promote the guilty.'' A radio station in the northern province of Corrientes claimed to have obtained a proclamation from rebel supporters which spelled out demands. The rebels, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Provincia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corrientes </ORGANIZATION> said, seek replacement of the current general staff and an immediate end to trials of military men accused of human rights abuses in a 1970s war against leftist subversives. At least 9,000 Argentines `` disappeared'' during that time and are presumed dead. The station also said the rebels sought special budget treatment for the armed forces. Army spending has been drastically slashed by a government plagued by deficit spending, triple-digit annual inflation and a $ 56 billion foreign debt.
