<FIRST>u i AM-Gorbachev-AtHomeandAbroad Bjt   12-03 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-At Home and Abroad, Bjt,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Leaders Trip May Divert Attention From Domestic Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> sets out this week on a trip to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> that will grab headlines around the world and may distract some attention from his problems at home. The Soviet leader is juggling ethnic violence in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, nationalist fever in the Baltic republics to the north and a pervasive sense that food and other essentials are becoming more difficult to find despite his promise that perestroika will make life better. The fires he is trying to control are breaking out at least in part because his new tolerance for dissent permits the fanning of long-smoldering embers without the harsh police-state crackdowns that would have been inevitable here only a few years ago. At the same time, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is moving ahead with the overhaul of the political system that he insists is needed in order to institutionalize democracy and block the bureaucracy from sliding back into stagnation. Some Western diplomats have suggested the Soviet president's travels are aimed at bolstering his image as a world leader at a time when chronic food shortages and public opposition raise questions about the success of his administration at home But both Soviet and Western analysts agree the trip is likely to buttress his efforts to integrate the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> into the world community and advance the improvement in East-West relations. That, they say, is the first step on a long road toward reordering domestic priorities in order to divert huge sums now allocated to defense and military aid and direct them toward improving the quality and availability of goods and services at home. `` It's reasonable to think that part of the motivation for the trip is to polish his image as a leader and effective statesman abroad,'' said one Western diplomat who studies Soviet affairs but asked not to be identified. `` The prestige that goes with all of that may help him play a role and could cause a certain distraction from domestic problems that seem so difficult to move or resolve.'' But the Western analyst and a Soviet foreign affairs specialist, who also spoke on condition of anonymity, agreed that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s trip is consistent with his stated goal of pressing for improved relations with the West in order to build and new and better life for his people at home `` The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> does n't have the resources to sustain the investment it's been making in foreign aid and defense,'' the diplomat said, adding the government `` must apply those resources to domestic problems'' if <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reform program, which he calls perestroika, or restructuring, is to succeed. The source noted that Western intelligence estimates place Soviet defense spending at 15 percent to 25 percent of the nation's gross national product, which is at least 2.5 times the comparable ratio spent by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` Even the lower end of that range would be enormous by world standards,'' the analyst said. `` The upper end would be truly staggering.'' But beyond the numbers, the source added, the military now monopolizes the nation's scientific and technological resources, leaving the rest of Soviet society relatively impoverished and unable to pull itself out of its backwardness. The Soviet source, in a separate interview, said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s trip will be aimed largely at dispelling the image many in the West share of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> as an enemy. `` We ca n't afford to finance revolution anymore,'' the source said. `` Now we must settle these regional conflicts and develop friendly relations with those who want to see us at the enemy.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> only recently disclosed his plan to address the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, say farewell to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and greet <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s successor, and meet with <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> and <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>. But he has been extraordinarily active this fall in pressing for improved relations, particularly with <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Since September, he has received leaders from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, has visited <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and on Saturday discussed with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s foreign minister the need for a Soviet-Chinese summit within the next six months. `` He's very much a realist,'' one source said, `` and as a realist, he knows he must dispel the ` enemy image' and develop a network of relationships with other countries before he can permit massive reductions in military spending and a reallocation of resources.''
