rs saw handwritten pages in which <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> vowed to care about <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s hair, clothes, work, problems, diet, future, teeth and other concerns. In another paper, she wrote 10 times that `` anger is destructive'' and that `` self-defense is regressive.'' <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> convinced Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> that she had belonged to a sado-masochistic cult, then encouraged her to imagine the details after convincing her she had amnesia, she testified. It was in this climate, the prosecution alleges, that an abused and neglected <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> was hurt on the night of Nov. 1, 1987. Hours later, <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, smoking cocaine, admitted knocking the child down and said it was because she stared at him, Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> testified. <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> died four days later of a brain injury. Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> was arrested with <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> after the little girl's death, but charges against her were dropped and she agreed to testify against him The prosecution contends that Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>, who lost her job when she frequently missed work because of injuries and then spent most of her time confined to the family's <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> apartment, was herself too much of a victim to have helped the child. `` I can liken it to being a prisoner of war,'' Ms. <PERSON> Segal </PERSON> said Saturday. The battered spouse syndrome, Ms. <PERSON> Segal </PERSON> said, is `` a process of brainwashing where you end up not really knowing what you think, what you believe, what's right, what's wrong. ... Gradually, there's an erosion of spirit, of will, of judgment. Its victims often are those who `` tend to be a bit timid, possibly fearful of the unknown,'' she said. Testimony showed that Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> tried to run away six times. Once, she changed her mind because she feared violent retaliation, she said. Once, a friend's brother told her she was being disloyal to <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>; once, she went to a <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> social services agency, where a staff member asked <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> to come get her. `` Generally, what you find is an alliance of sorts: physical or emotional abuse, which is then, almost like a seesaw, balanced by some occasional nurturing,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Segal </PERSON>. `` For a great many women, if they did leave, where would they go _ especially with children?'' In addition to <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>, Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> and <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> had another illegally adopoted child, a boy who has since been returned to his natural mother. Ms. <PERSON> Segal </PERSON> said patient confidentiality precluded her discussing specifics of Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>'s case. `` She's been very courageous and is handling herself beautifully _ that's my personal opinion,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Segal </PERSON>, adding that she also had told that to Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>. `` I think that now, people may feel a little safer talking about some of this. It might encourage women to seek help, to try to get out of eroding situations in their lives and to know that they're not alone.
