<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> skirmished over farm subsidies on Saturday as trade ministers of more than 100 nations began arriving for global free-trade talks. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> is under heavy pressure from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as well as major grain-exporting nations, such as <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and host <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, to reduce the protection it gives its farmers. `` It's very clear that many divergences still exist -LRB- on agriculture -RRB-. I hope -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> is coming in like <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claus </LOCATION> with a bag full of realistic proposals,'' <PERSON> Willy </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Clercq </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s minister for finance and foreign trade, said in a news conference. However, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiators stuck to a tough line. `` No deal is better than a bad deal,'' <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmer </PERSON>, a top <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegate, said in a separate press conference. Trade ministers of 105 countries, including 96 member nations of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, began arriving Saturday for the midterm review of free-trade talks under the auspices of the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, European, Japanese and Canadian negotiators met in an informal session on Saturday to review the prospects for the talks, which officially begin Monday. <PERSON> Holmer </PERSON> said the meeting `` crystallized the differences that exist'' between the parties, apparently referring mainly to the dispute over farm subsidies. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON