<HEAD>Connecticut Metal Company Fined In Acid Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH WINDSOR, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A company where a worker died after inhaling toxic fumes when he fell face-down in a puddle of a highly corrosive form of acid will be fined $ 6,480 for various safety violations, federal officials announced. <ORGANIZATION> Metals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Testing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Windsor </LOCATION> was cited for eight infractions, some of which contributed to the October death, said <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, industrial hygiene supervisor at the <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> office. The company tests metals for aircraft parts at its plant and uses hydrofluoric acid to etch titanium parts. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cunningham </PERSON>, 29, of <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> lost his footing in October while carrying an open bucket of the acid and fell face-first into the toxic, highly corrosive substance. Toxic inhalation was listed as the cause of death, and his body was also burned. Two other workers were treated after inhaling the acid fumes. `` They -LRB- Metals Testing officials -RRB- did n't follow appropriate working practices for handling corrosive materials,'' <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> said Friday. `` What caused the death was that the material spilled. It would n't have spilled if it was being carried in a closed container.'' Company President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLisle </PERSON> declined comment on the <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> findings. The company can appeal the fines, <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> said the citations alleged two counts of insufficient safety training, two counts of lack of protective clothing, failure to provide an appropriate first