<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An official of the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear plant says he would like to see a joint U.S.-Soviet reactor built to help prevent future accidents. `` I think that only by joint efforts can we create a new, modern type of reactor which could exclude the negative impact on the environment and exclude the possibility of such accidents which happened at Three Mile Island and <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Borisyuk </PERSON>, deputy secretary of <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION>, said in an interview Friday. <PERSON> Borisyuk </PERSON> is one of 10 Soviets and 11 Americans on the Global Environment Commission of the U.S.-U.S.S.R. Emerging Leaders Summit, a weeklong gathering of more than 340 Americans and Soviets that began Thursday. The delegates spent much of Saturday watching the <ORGANIZATION> Army-Navy </ORGANIZATION> football game at Veterans Stadium and visiting the <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> and Independence Hall. <PERSON> Ilona </PERSON> <PERSON> Zheleznyako </PERSON>, 30, a housing construction engineer from <LOCATION> Tinda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, touched the historic bell, which rang in July 1776 to announce the adoption of the Declaration of Independence. She said she felt `` a good feeling of freedom and liberty.'' <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Chelnokov </PERSON>, 34, said he was impressed with the longevity of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Constitution. `` In our country, there is a rethinking of some of the ideas of our revolution, and we are now reconstructing a society which is only 70 years old,'' he said. `` So it is amazing that something that is three times as old is still working.'' The summit is focused on private meetings of 16 commissions assigned areas of discussion such as the environment, military affairs, religion, science, business, the media and the arts. The <ORGANIZATION> Global </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> will look at such topics as global warming, ozone depletion, acid rain, ocean waste, economic development and international agreements. The conference comes as the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has begun re-examining conservation practices and giving citizens a greater voice in environmental protection. The 1986 explosion and fire at <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> was the world's worst nuclear accident. It killed at least 33 people, sent a radioactive cloud around the globe and made an area within a 40-mile radius of the plant uninhabitable. At <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s Three Mile Island reactor, equipment failures and human error led to a loss of coolant and partial core meltdown in 1979. `` The main lesson is the imperfection of technology that is used at atomic power plants both in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and in the <LOCATION> U.S.S.R. </LOCATION>, and also imperfection of personnel training,'' <PERSON> Borisyuk </PERSON> said. He said he believes nuclear energy remains the safest and least-polluting form of energy, if properly managed.
