<SECOND>AM-Israel-Hanukkah,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Begins Feast of Lights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Candles were lighted in the windows of homes across the country Saturday as Jews began celebrating the eight-day Festival of Lights, or Hanukkah, which commemorates the victory of the Jews over the Syrians 2,000 years ago. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio broadcast festive songs throughout the night, and bakeries served the special sugar-coated jelly doughnuts that are a holiday tradition. Hanukkah marks the victory of the Jews over the Greco-Syrian kingdom in 165 B.C. The kingdom had tried to impose its culture on the Jews and desecrated the holy temple in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> with statues of <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> gods. The statues were regarded as pagan idols, which are anathema to Jews. The Jews rose in revolt, destroyed the statues and drove the Syrians out of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. According to legend, when the Jews tried to relight the temple's eternal flame, they found enough oil for one day But the fire miraculously lasted for eight days. To commemorate the holiday, candles are lighted at sunset for eight consecutive nights. They are placed one at a time in a special eight-branch candelabra called a menorah. Fried foods such as potato pancakes and doughnuts are eaten to commemorate the miracle of the oil. The festival is celebrated by religious and secular Jews as a holiday that not only marks the ancient Jewish victory but also reminds Israelis of their desire to perpetuate national Jewish identity.
</TEXT>
