<HEAD>Jewish Holiday of Hanukkah Begins Tonight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The eight-day Jewish festival of Hanukkah begins at sundown today, marking the an ancient victory of the <ORGANIZATION> Maccabees </ORGANIZATION> over a Syrian attempt to stamp out Jewish worship. The holiday is marked by songs, games and gift-giving. On the first evening, one candle customarily is lit in an eight-tapered candelabrum, the menorah, with an additional one lit on successive days until all eight of them burn. The observance recalls the cleansing and rededication of the ancient Temple in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, which the Syrian oppressors had converted into a scene of pagan idols and prostitution. Legend has it that only enough oil was available to keep the rededicated temple lamps burning for one day, but they miraculously burned for eight. The holiday lasts through next Sunday.
