<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The charismatic leader of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s latest military insurrection, <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> Col. <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Seineldin </PERSON>, once rejected a medal for his service in the <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> war because his troops were defeated. Friends and colleagues interviewed Friday described <PERSON> Seineldin </PERSON>, who was trained in part at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION>, as a widely respected officer known for ultranationalist political views. The 54-year-old officer led at least 400 backers, who holed up in an army base outside the capital Friday and battled government troops. <PERSON> Seineldin </PERSON> was born a Moslem of Syrian-Lebanese parents but converted to Roman Catholicism. A superior once described him as `` holding the fanaticism of a convert'' in all his endeavors. Despite a distinguished military career, <PERSON> Seineldin </PERSON> was passed over for promotion to brigadier general last year and faced the prospect of eventual forced retirement. He said Friday he was not seeking to overthrow <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s constitutional government `` but to restore military honor to the army. <PERSON> Seineldin </PERSON> said he also wanted a review of trials `` that punish the just and promote the guilty.'' It was an apparent reference to trials of military officers accused of human rights violations during efforts by military governments in the 1970s to put down leftist subversion. <PERSON> Seineldin </PERSON> has denied involvement in the disappearance of about 9,000 Argentines during the anti-leftist campaign. After spending the last four years in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, first as Argentine military attache and then as an instructor to the Panamanian <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Seineldin </PERSON> was believed to have returned to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> on Thursday via neighboring <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> to lead the revolt. He was eager to come home, his wife <PERSON> Marta </PERSON> <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Labiau </PERSON> told the private news agency DyN in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, `` because it was beginning to look like he had been sent into exile.'' <PERSON> Seineldin </PERSON> was born Nov. 12, 1934, in the town of <LOCATION> Concepcion </LOCATION> <LOCATION> del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, 140 miles north of <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>. His father was a businessman and citrus grower. A graduate of the <ORGANIZATION> Argentine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION>, he rose rapidly in rank, specializing in infantry commando tactics. He was assigned to lead commandos on the Argentina-Chile border in 1978 when the two neighbors nearly went to war in a dispute over three tiny islands. Promoted to colonel, <PERSON> Seineldin </PERSON> led a commando unit that participated in the occupation of the British-held <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> on April 2, 1982. The Argentines, who call the islands the <LOCATION> Malvinas </LOCATION>, were defeated by a <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> task force 74 days later. When <PERSON> Seineldin </PERSON> was called to testify in human rights abuses trials in 1984, troops formerly under his command gathered outside the court to cheer him and shouted, `` We'll go back to the Malvinas!''
