 has concluded. The federal agency continue accepting any new evidence until it drafts a final report on the crash in about six months. <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> sent a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Alger </PERSON> dated Sept. 15, 1988, notifying him of `` aircarrier operations bulletin No. 8-884, takeoff warning systems checks.'' `` The accident in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> has focused the nation on the takeoff warning system; therefore, we are requesting a little more than your usual prompt reply,'' said <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> in his letter to <PERSON> Alger </PERSON>. <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said in response to questions that `` sometimes it does take a while to distribute information to working levels, to my level,'' and explained he did n't specifically know how the June 17 letter was routed. <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said the bulletin would have been relayed through several offices and reviewed by several individuals. `` I'm not sure we call it a dead letter,'' <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilot </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said his group was investigating whether the delay in spreading notice of the inspections was normal or unusual. <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> also noted that the issue may only be on the periphery of the public hearing. `` The testing is irrelevant to this investigation only if it was a no-flap situation,'' <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> said. `` We continue to dispute this assertion.'' <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> has steadfastly maintained during the federal inquiry that the three-man <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> crew, who testified earlier, were the victims of a split-flap configuation in which the plane's outer flaps are extended or in place for a takeoff while the i