<FIRST>r a PM-Shuttle-BlueCube     12-03 0945</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle-Blue Cube,0966</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inside Mysterious Blue Cube Scientists Track Military Satellites</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Step into the mysterious, windowless Blue Cube, where 2,000 engineers and scientists working furiously with old, slow computers will soon have a new task _ tracking and controlling the $ 500 million spy satellite to be deployed by Atlantis. Giant screens, rows of terminals and bulky machines fill a warehouse-size room in the military's ultra-secret satellite tracking center, receiving millions of bits of coded information each second on the location and operation of hundreds of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and foreign satellites. The Cube can order one of the more than 50 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military satellites to snap photos of suspected troop movements and drop off the film in a parachute package to an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> plane for a midair pickup. It can adjust a satellite's orbit, solar energy panels, cameras or other gear. Special attention is focused now on the new `` bird'' to be placed in orbit Saturday by the shuttle, a radar satellite code-named Lacrosse that is designed to spy on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and guide the stealth bomber. The Cube, officially called the Consolidated Space Test Center, is run by the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> in the heart of <LOCATION> Silicon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. Next door are the <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ames </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Missiles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc Neither journalists nor others without top security clearance are allowed past the high fences and armed guards surrounding the pale blue building. However, interviews with <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials with access to the Cube, all of whom asked not to be identified, reveal a beehive of activity as a crack team of physicists, electrical and mechanical engineers and computer scientists cope with a crush of signals to and from satellites. `` The adrenalin flows, you work 18 hours a day, but you do n't feel tired at all,'' said one veteran of several satellite launches `` You suffer battle fatigue when it's over, but during the mission people get really hyped. This is their time and they're going to make it work. When you run into obstacles because the system is clumsy, just sheer energy makes it happen.'' The Cube has been in operation since 1959, virtually from the start of the space program. Despite the expenditure of several hundred million dollars to upgrade the computer and data distribution system over the past six years, most of the computers in the Cube are two or three generations old. They are reliable workhorses, built by <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and others in the 1970s and early 1980s, but are much slower, less efficient and more expensive to run than newer models at many companies in <LOCATION> Silicon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. Instead of state of the art, the Cube's tubes and software programs remain `` antiquated,'' one systems expert said, because of government procurement policies. `` <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> and the military are stuck in this Catch-22,'' the systems expert said. `` It's hard to sell missions and get money. So people have to design minimal systems that use equipment from past missions, and they end up putting systems in place that are terribly engineered.'' He added, though, that `` very exceptional people at <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> and the military make the system work despite the system.'' Until a few years ago, the Cube was the nation's only control center for military satellites, a place so secret that officials used to deny even its existence. Located within bazooka range of two highways and close to three earthquake faults, the Cube's vulnerability led to a $ 3.5 billion overhaul to bring it up to date and build a command center with similar capabilities at <ORGANIZATION> Falcon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>. Those two centers are linked to eight <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> tracking sites around the world, including <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, as well as other <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> stations and a main ground station at <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sands </LOCATION>, N.M The Tracking and Data Relay Satellite System, or TDRSS, is used to keep watch over all satellites, friendly and unfriendly, and any other `` space junk'' or debris from defunct satellites that could get in their way. TDRSS West, a satellite in orbit 22,000 miles over the western <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, was the main tracker in space until September, when the shuttle Discovery placed TDRSS East in geosynchronous orbit 22,000 miles over the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>. For the launch of the new spy satellite, the military and civilian teams in the Cube and in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> will take over control of the satellite from <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> once they get the word `` the bird is in orbit.'' Because of secrecy requirements, nearly all the information from the TDRSS satellites and the spy satellite is fully encrypted. The ground station at <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sands </LOCATION>, a huge computer complex that is perhaps the most modern communications facility in the world, receives the information on two bands: C-band at 56,000 bits per second and KU-band at 300 million bits per second. The system can run several channels of each band simultaneously, taking in a total of more than a billion bits of information per second. The signals are then broken up into multiple channels at lower rates easier to handle, rebroadcast back up to military satellites and down again to the Cube and <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, where they are monitored by the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> round the clock. The first job after the shuttle drops off the spy satellite is to order the firing of positioning rockets to stabilize the satellite in orbit. The exact position and type of orbit are secret, although some experts call such secrecy `` a silly game,'' since Soviet tracking stations can tell where all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> satellites are anyway.
</TEXT>
