<HEAD>Atlantis Rockets Heading Back To Cape</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Atlantis' twin booster rockets were heading back to land by way of sea today after helping send the shuttle into space. Two ships towed the twin boosters toward <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION>, near the Kennedy Space Center, after they were recovered in rough seas 160 miles out in the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>. They dropped with parachutes within eight miles of the recovery ships after Friday morning's successful launch, the second since the Challenger disaster blamed on booster rockets. `` Everything appeared to be very nominal -LRB- normal -RRB-. There appeared to be no external leakage or anything like that,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, a motor technical assistant for the <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> who came to Kennedy Space Center for the launch. Divers from the recovery ships took a quick look at the boosters, tossed in rough seas with winds of 20 to 30 knots, and saw no obvious damage, said <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Diller </PERSON>. The divers removed the parachutes that slowed the boosters' plummet, then attached flotation devices and cables from the 149-foot boosters to the two recovery ships and began removing pockets of water, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> said The 200,000-pound steel casings were expected at <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION> this afternoon. After cleaning and other work here, they will be returned to the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> plant of manufacturer <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for inspection and refitting. The boosters have drawn close attention since their failure was blamed for the Jan. 28, 1986, Challenger explosion that killed all seven astronauts aboard. The <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that investigated the disaster said a booster O-ring that failed to seal in cold weather allowed flame to escape and ignited the main fuel tank. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> spent $ 800 million to make 145 changes in the booster design and for testing before the Discovery launch Sept. 29. The massive rockets have 11 major components and are manufactured in four segments joined at the seams. `` There are so many parts, so many things that could go wrong,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>. But he added, `` I was not nearly as apprehensive'' as he was during the Discovery launch. `` On that one, there was a lot of apprehension. I stood there and cried.'' When fully loaded with 1.1 million pounds of propellant, each booster weighs 1.3 million pounds and produces 3.3 million pounds of thrust that give the orbiter 80 percent of the power needed to lift it from the launch pad into orbit.
