<HEAD>Searching for a Cure for Market Malaise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the closing weeks of 1988, Wall Streeters are still groping for the right prescription to reinvigorate a stock market that has languished all year. While the market's maladies have resisted all remedies, they have not turned out as severe as they threatened to become after the crash in October 1987. After all, barring a sudden sharp drop this month, stock prices will close out this year, as they did last year, showing a net gain. But that prospect stirred little elation among the brokers who gathered here this past week for the annual convention of their principal trade group, the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Trading volume in all markets remains down, depressing a prime source of the Street's revenues. Individual investors are still opting for the safe haven of certificates of deposit or money market funds and shunning stocks. In addition, the gains the market has managed to record have stemmed largely from takeover and buyout activity like the bidding war for <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> that has dominated recent financial headlines. Whatever short-term benefits buyouts bring to brokers and their customers, most analysts agree they have by no means solved the problem of restoring confidence in the market. On the contrary, they have raised fears of new shocks when the superstructure of debt created by the buyouts is sooner or later tested in a business downturn. `` In the long term, I think it's unhealthy for the markets,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardiman </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION>, which supervises the over-the-counter market. Scandals over insider trading and other abuses also still cloud the outlook. `` There is the matter of industry image, or reputation, or integrity _ call it what you will,'' said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is undeniable that it has been tarnished in the past few years.'' While <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> argued that some criticisms of Wall Street's behavior have gone beyond what is justified, he also acknowledged that they have stung `` In my view, there is no magic potion that can be taken to produce a happy new world, and national media campaigns are not the answer,'' he said. Then, too, there is the question of whether investigations and reform measures since the 1987 market collapse have done enough to restore faith in the mechanism of the marketplace itself. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, thinks not. He urged that the new administration and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> appoint a commission to do a long-term study of the markets. More than 13 months after the fact, he said, `` I do n't think anyone understands last October.'' Those who hold out hope for revived enthusiasm in the near future say their conviction lies in the very caution and pessimism that are so prevalent now. They point to measures of investment advisory sentiment that have lately turned as gloomy as at any time since just before the start of the 1982-87 bull market. And indeed, adherents of this school of `` contrary opinion'' made their presence felt in the past week's trading activity. The Dow Jones industrial average of 30 industrials rose 17.60 to 2,092.28. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> composite index gained 2.39 to 153.02; the <ORGANIZATION> NASDAQ </ORGANIZATION> composite index for the over-the-counter market added 7.53 to 373.91; and the Amex market value index was up 4.08 to 295.27. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> averaged 132.54 million shares a day, against 107.86 million the previous week. With so much money stockpiled in CDs and money market investments, a drop in interest rates might well give stocks a big lift, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> brokerage executive who was chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> the past two years. In the crash, he said, `` the public was bruised and frightened, but not broken. I suspect we could have a surprisingly good year in 1989.''
</TEXT>
